AI-Assisted Experimental Avionics Laboratory

Version: 0.1
Author: Carl Suttle
Date: 2026

1. Purpose

This project explores AI-assisted avionics development.

The goal is to determine whether a technically minded pilot using AI tools can design and prototype flight instrumentation systems that previously required large engineering teams.

The project is experimental and research-oriented.

Primary motivations:

explore pilot-centric instrumentation

accelerate avionics prototyping

evaluate AI as an engineering collaborator

document a repeatable development method

The broader hypothesis is:

AI reduces implementation difficulty so that domain expertise becomes the primary driver of innovation.

2. Project Philosophy

This project follows several principles.

2.1 Domain Knowledge Drives Design

Aviation knowledge determines system requirements.

AI assists implementation but does not define system behavior.

2.2 Rapid Prototyping

Engineering follows a prototype loop:

identify instrumentation problem

conceptual design

AI-assisted implementation

bench testing

flight test or simulation

observation and documentation

iterate

AI greatly accelerates step 3.

2.3 Demonstration Over Perfection

The goal is first working demonstrations, not finished products.

The key moment of interest is when an idea first works.

This validates feasibility and allows further exploration.

2.4 Pilot-Centric Instrumentation

Many avionics systems prioritize sensors or automation.

This project prioritizes pilot situational awareness.

Questions include:

What information does a pilot truly need?

When do instruments mislead?

How can energy state be better represented?

3. Engineering Method

This project represents a new workflow:

AI-Assisted Domain Engineering

Traditional engineering:

Idea → Engineering team → Implementation → Prototype

AI-assisted engineering:

Domain insight → AI collaboration → Prototype

Implementation becomes faster, shifting the challenge to:

system architecture

validation

human factors

